"bio":{"display_name":"George Norton","first_name":"George","last_name":"Norton","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"george-norton-1782"},"I00055":{"id":"I00055","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1702,"month":10,"day":8,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1751,"month":3,"day":30,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"mother_research_notes":"Margaret Hart — daughter of Capt. Thomas Hart (X00031), son of Stephen Hart (X00034)","father_research_notes":"Asahel Strong Sr. (b. Nov 14, 1668 Northampton MA) — married Margaret Hart, daughter of Capt. Thomas Hart (X00031)"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00103","children_ids":["H00293","H00294","H00295","H00296","H00297","H00298","H00299","H00300"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1729,"date_month":1,"date_day":8}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 103"}],"gender":"male","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":null,"primary_url":null,"primary_url_label":null},"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"I00900","display_label":"Both Strong men who married Hooker descendants, 84 years apart","link_text":"Judge Elisha Beebe Strong"}],"bio":{"title":"Captain","display_name":"Captain Asahel Strong Jr.","first_name":"Asahel","last_name":"Strong","suffix":"Jr.","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"His Hooker marriage echoed down two more generations","body":"When Captain Asahel Strong Jr. married Sarah Hooker in 1729 at Farmington, Connecticut — a great-great-granddaughter of Rev. Thomas Hooker — he began a pattern that would echo through generations: their great-great-grandson Asahel Hooker Strong was born in 1776 with 'Hooker' preserved as his middle name, and 84 years after the first marriage, Judge Elisha Beebe Strong married another Thomas Hooker descendant, Dolly Goodwin Hooker, at Canandaigua, New York in 1813. By 1866, that second union had produced Beebe Hooker Strong of Milwaukee, the fourth person in the Strong family to carry the Hooker name — connecting the original Farmington parsonage to the Wisconsin frontier across 137 years."}],"slug":"asahel-strong-jr-1702"},"H00103":{"id":"H00103","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":4,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1708,"month":4,"day":16,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1777,"month":9,"day":18,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00030","mother_id":"I00031"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 103"},{"short":"Native Northeast Portal","url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/hooker-ruth-1708-1777"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00055","children_ids":["H00293","H00294","H00295","H00296","H00297","H00298","H00299","H00300"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1751,"date_year":1729,"date_month":1,"date_day":8},{"children_ids":[],"spouse_id":"I00134","marriage_number":2,"date_year":1772,"date_month":11,"date_day":19}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"H00795","display_label":"Hooker women who married Strongs in 1729 and 1813","link_text":"Dolly Goodwin Hooker"}],"gender":"female","narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Eight children with Capt. Asahel Strong Jr.","body":"She married Capt. Asahel Strong Jr. on January 8, 1729 and bore him eight children — including Rev. Cyprian Strong of Chatham. Asahel was a grandson of Stephen Hart through his mother Margaret Hart, closing another loop in the Hart-Hooker network."},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"Lost three children in September 1736","body":"In a single ten-day span — September 6 to 15, 1736 — three of her young children died: Lois and Ruth on the same day, then Elnathan nine days later. The cluster strongly suggests an epidemic moving through Farmington."},{"number":3,"category":"marriage","header":"Second husband Solomon Whitman lived to 93","body":"After Capt. Asahel Strong's death she married Solomon Whitman, who was Town Clerk at 92 and made a pair of shoes on his 90th birthday. He died at 93 from over-fatigue settling a fence dispute between two brothers."}],"number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"bio":{"display_name":"Ruth Hooker Whitman","first_name":"Ruth","last_name":"Whitman","maiden_name":"Hooker","married_names":["Strong","Whitman"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"ruth-whitman-1708"},"H00030":{"id":"H00030","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":3,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1664,"month":2,"day":20,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1746,"month":2,"day":21,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00007","mother_id":"I00006"},"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 30"},{"short":"Native Northeast Portal","url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/hooker-john-1664-1746"},{"short":"L.J. Hooker 1898","full":"L.J. Hooker, 'Edward Hooker, Commander, U.S. Navy,' The Old Northwest Genealogical Quarterly (Columbus, Ohio, 1898-), VII, 12"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00031","children_ids":["H00095","H00096","H00097","H00098","H00099","H00100","H00101","H00102","H00103","H00104"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1687,"date_month":11,"date_day":24}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","notes":"Col. Wadsworth's son Daniel Wadsworth founded the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford — a monument with Hooker family kinship interest. Research needed to confirm Mehitable Russell's Hooker descent line. Warren 1887 confirms: Elizabeth Standley married John Wadsworth — their son Daniel Wadsworth founded the Wadsworth Atheneum.","related_id":"X00035","display_label":"was his father-in-law, honored in the Indian wars","link_text":"Capt. John Standley"},{"type":"civic_peer","notes":"Capt. Thomas Hart b. ca. 1644, d. Aug 27, 1726 age 82. Son of Stephen Hart (X00034). Brother of John Hart who survived the 1666 fire (X00033). Not in this tree through marriage — noted as civic context only.","related_id":"X00034","display_label":"helped govern Farmington alongside him for decades","link_text":"Stephen Hart"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"T00387","display_label":"married a descendant of both Hooker and Standley","link_text":"Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00418","display_label":"served Hartford’s founding-family public life alongside him","link_text":"Rev. Daniel Wadsworth"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00453","display_label":"was his wife’s sister and Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth’s grandmother","link_text":"Elizabeth Standley"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00031","display_label":"fathered four children who married four of his own","link_text":"Capt. John Hart"},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"I00053","display_label":"Both served as Connecticut Colony Supreme Court judges.","link_text":"Hon. Daniel Edwards"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00089","display_label":"was the cousin whose Indian Neck deed he registered","link_text":"William Hooker"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"X00263","display_label":"signed a Tunxis dispossession deed as his descendant’s in-law","link_text":"Lt. John Mix"},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H00439","display_label":"shared his entanglement in Tunxis affairs, decades apart","link_text":"Ezekiel Cowles Jr."},{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X00045","display_label":"was called with him one of Farmington’s two prominent men","link_text":"Captain Thomas Hart"}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM004","plot_notes":"Memento Mori Cemetery, Farmington, Hartford County, Connecticut. Same cemetery as his father Rev. Samuel Hooker (H00007)."},"gender":"male","tags":["politician","judge","compiler_ancestor"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Connecticut Superior Court judge, 1724-1732","primary_url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/hooker-john-1664-1746","primary_url_label":"Native Northeast Portal — John Hooker biography"},"documents":["DOC004"],"residence":{"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"law","header":"Judge of Connecticut Colony's Supreme Court","body":"He served as Judge of the Supreme Court of Connecticut Colony from 1724 to 1732 and as Speaker of the Lower House. He also served as witness, certifying Assistant, and Registrar in the 1733 Sue Squa land deed — three official roles in a single transaction."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"He defended Tunxis land rights in court","body":"In 1738, John Hooker provided a formal statement to the Connecticut General Court that ninety acres at Indian Neck had 'always belonged' to the Tunxis tribe — an unusual act of testimony on behalf of the indigenous people whose land his own ancestors had settled near."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"The elm fell so someone could walk straight","body":"His father gave him a site on the west side of Farmington's main street, where he built under the branches of a great elm. The tree became famous through all the region for the company that gathered beneath it — three generations of Hookers lived in its shade before a later owner cut it down to straighten the sidewalk."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"The bell tolled — Hooker stepped out first","body":"A chronicler recorded that every Sunday the bell rang, then began tolling; at the first stroke, Hooker issued from his house and proceeded to the Meeting House. The minister walked from his house. Whoever arrived first waited at the door; together they entered — at which the bell stopped and all the congregation arose."},{"number":5,"category":"character","header":"The Sabbath ended when Hooker touched his gate","body":"The holiness of Sunday was supposed to end at sunset — but no child in the town dared stir until John Hooker gave the signal. When the sun sank, he walked to his gate and leaned on it; open flew the doors and out came the children with a wild rush and shout."},{"number":6,"category":"character","header":"Dark hair, dark eyes — dignity commanding respect","body":"His grandson described him: \"Dark hair and dark eyes, and a dignity in his air and expression that procured profound respect.\" A fine looking man, tall, very erect, and had a prominent large nose. He lived his entire life in Farmington, dying there in 1746 at age 81."}],"career":[{"role":"Justice and Register","organization":"Farmington, Connecticut","notes":"Served as justice and register of Farmington"},{"role":"Representative","organization":"Connecticut General Court","notes":"From Farmington. Served as Clerk two sessions; Speaker six sessions."},{"role":"Speaker","organization":"Connecticut General Court Lower House"},{"role":"Assistant","organization":"Colony of Connecticut"},{"role":"Judge, Superior Court","organization":"Colony of Connecticut","notes":"Served as judge of Superior Court concurrent with assistant role"},{"role":"Commissioner, Mohegan Sequestered Land","organization":"New London, Connecticut","notes":"Commissioner of the Mohegan's sequestered land at New London"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Hon. John Hooker","title":"Honorable","first_name":"John","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":[]},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"john-hooker-1664"},"I00031":{"id":"I00031","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1669,"month":7,"day":25,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1743,"month":2,"day":21,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00030","children_ids":["H00095","H00096","H00097","H00098","H00099","H00100","H00101","H00102","H00103","H00104"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1687,"date_month":11,"date_day":24,"location_country":"United States"}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entries 99-101"}],"parents":{"father_id":"X00035","mother_id":"X00036"},"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_marriage","related_id":"I00051","display_label":"Both married Hooker brothers — from two separate Stanley families.","link_text":"Mary Standley"},{"type":"founding_family_nexus","related_id":"X00032","display_label":"Their families united — three daughters married Hart brothers.","link_text":"Mary Moore Hart"},{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"X00453","display_label":"Her sister Elizabeth Standley married into the Wadsworth line.","link_text":"Elizabeth Standley"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Her father won distinction in the Indian wars","body":"Capt. John Standley was a man of wealth and high social position who had served as lieutenant and captain in the Indian wars. Her sister Elizabeth Standley's granddaughter married Col. Jeremiah Wadsworth, Commissary General of the Continental Army — Wadsworth's wife also descended from Rev. Thomas Hooker, making Wadsworth's children doubly connected to the Hooker line."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Abigail Standley Hooker","notes":"Also spelled 'Stanley' in EH entry 30; 'Standley' in entries 99-101","first_name":"Abigail","last_name":"Hooker","married_names":["Hooker"],"maiden_name":"Standley"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM004","plot_notes":"Memento Mori Cemetery, Farmington CT. SOURCE: FindAGrave."},"slug":"abigail-standley-1669"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}